<F P=101> BIOTECHNOLOGY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Netherlands: TNO Develops Test To Check If Cholesterol Is Hereditary </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR2202154094 Rijswijk BIONIEUWS in Dutch 15 Jan 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> BR2202154094 </F>
<F P=104>  Rijswijk BIONIEUWS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Dutch </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed MSC: "Test for Hereditary Cholesterol </F>
Defect"] 
  [Text] The TNO [Netherlands Organization for Applied 
Natural Science Research] has developed a test to determine 
whether a high cholesterol level is caused by a genetic defect. 
The defect in question is located in the gene close to the 
receptor responsible for cholesterol elimination [ldl-receptor] 
and causes an hereditary form of hypercholesteremia. The test 
is a combination of pcr [polymerase chain reaction] and 
gelelectrophoresis. Dr. Paola Lombardi from the TNO Institute 
for Studies on Aging and Vascular Diseases, who obtained her 
Ph.D. with this research, claims the test is nearly flawless. 
According to her, the test is not yet being used, but will be 
introduced in hospitals in the long term. The patients' veins 
have been constricting since birth, hence the importance of 
knowing whether hypercholesteremia is hereditary. 

</TEXT>

