Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Article: "Test Flights of Saab's JAS 39-Gripen Halted"] </F>
  [Text]Paris - Trollhaettan -- On 21 January, a spokesperson 
for Volvo Flygmotor, the aeronautical branch of Sweden's leading 
industrial group at Trollhaettan, announced that test flights of 
Sweden's Saab JAS 39-Gripen military aircraft have been halted 
as the result of the breakage, a week ago, of a blade inside the 
RM12 turbine engine that the aircraft is equipped with. 
  According to the spokesperson, Sweden's military authorities 
grew very circumspect after a Saab JAS 39-Gripen crashed on 8 
August 1993, during a demonstration, near the downtown area of 
Sweden's capital. The pilot could no longer steer the aircraft 
because of a failure in the control lever. 
  During a test bench session "sizable vibrations" 
were registered in the engine's turbine. 

</TEXT>

