<ABS>  Japan </ABS>
<DATE1>   2 March 1994 </DATE1>
<F P=100> Energy </F>
<H3> <TI>   Toshiba Develops Superconductor Magnet Without Using Liquid Helium </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94FE0211K Tokyo NIKKAN KOGYO SHIMBUN in Japanese 20 Nov 93 p 
5--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 94FE0211K </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIKKAN KOGYO SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:CSO 

  [Text] Toshiba Corp. (Fumio Sato, president) announced on 
19 November that it has developed a small superconductor magnet 
without using liquid helium, by commercializing a refrigerating 
machine that can cool to the temperature of liquid helium 
(absolute temperature of 4.2K=-269C). Since 
conventional refrigeration machines have not been able to go 
below 10K, niobium titanium superconductor magnets could 
not be used, but since with this new refrigeration machine 
cooling to 4.2K is possible and the container is 
approximately one-third the size of conventional ones, it is 
possible to generate a strong magnetic field of six tesla in a 
large diameter room temperature space, which has an internal 
diameter of 18 cm. Toshiba believes that there will be a great 
expansion in the fields using superconductor magnets. 
  The superconductor magnet system that was developed 
incorporates a small refrigeration machine that is an 
improvement on the Gifford-McMahon (GM) type refrigeration 
machines that are most commonly in use at present. Since 
conventional refrigeration machines could not cool below 
10K, niobium 3-tin, etc. had to be used, but by finding 
regenerative materials with large specific heats below 10K, 
Toshiba was able to attain cooling in the 4K range. 
  In addition, an oxide superconductor which has low thermal 
conductivity and in which current flows well in a strong 
magnetic field is used for the power lead that brings current to 
the superconductor coil, and this is connected to the reduction 
in cooling temperature. 
  With this it is possible to use the main current niobium 
titanium superconductor magnet, for which liquid helium cooling 
had been necessary, with a direct cooling refrigeration machine, 
and a strong magnetic field can be generated with a small unit. 
  The container that accommodates the magnetic field is 65 cm 
wide, 50 cm deep and 49 cm high, a small size about that of a 25 
inch television set, and all that must be done when it is used 
is to turn on a switch. 
  Toshiba says that almost all superconductor magnets, such as 
those for industry and research, can use this refrigeration 
machine, and it will release users from the complexity of using 
liquid helium cooling. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-21117 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "jpjst008__l94020" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   JPRS-JST-94-008-L </AU>
Document Type:JPRS 
Document Title:Science &amp; Technology 

</HEADER>

<ABS>  Japan </ABS>
<DATE1>   2 March 1994 </DATE1>
<F P=100> Lasers, Sensors, Optics </F>
<H3> <TI>   Matsushita Electric Develops First Surface-Emission Laser OEIC </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94P60096A Tokyo KAGAKU KOGYO NIPPO in Japanese 8 Dec 93 p 
5--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 94P60096A </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KAGAKU KOGYO NIPPO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:CSO 

  [Text] The Semiconductor Technology Center of Matsushita 
Electric Industrial Co., Ltd. developed the world's first 
surface-emission laser optoelectronic integrated circuit (OEIC) 
which can operate 10 times as fast as a conventional matrix-type 
surface-emission laser. The center designed a unique system in 
which transistors are mounted on lasers (transistor-on-laser) 
and lined up 64 lasers in an array-formation in a cell that is a 
480 micron square. Each laser has a built-in transistor as its 
driver. As a result, this accomplishment makes 10 gigahertz 
high-speed operations functionally possible and it will open up 
the way to the attainment of optical computers and optical 
switchboards. 
  Innovations in the CPU [Central Processing Unit] and such 
have advanced the speed of computers. However, transmission 
delays become a problem when there is an interchange among them 
on networks. It has been pointed out that there are limits to 
the present method used to amplify the signal by converting 
optical communications into electricity. 
  Therefore, there is a strong need for optical switches and 
such which will make ultra high speed circuitry possible for the 
switching of optical signals, without conversion, between 
optical fibers. The surface-emission laser is expected to be one 
of the basic technologies to make this possible. 
  Although a chip has been developed which has integrated over 
a thousand elements in the surface-emission laser, the 
conventional product uses a matrix form of circuitry which needs 
a large electric current to change the frequency of the laser. 
Moreover, the circuit distance from the driver transistor is so 
great that it makes high-speed operations difficult. 
  In this instance, the device developed by Matsushita 
Electric 
has 64 0.98 nanometer wavelength surface-emission lasers each 
integrated with a driver transistor. This structure uses a 
unique method of putting the transistor on top of the laser. By 
doing this, Matsushita made it possible to increase the 
high-speed operations to more than 10 times that of the 
matrix-type and also made it possible to increase the density 
and reduce the area to one third of the latter type. A special 
quality is that it is feasible to increase the speed up of 10 
gigahertz and it is expected that this development will 
drastically promote the utilization of optical computers and 
optical switches. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-21118 </DOCNO>
