<ABS>  Japan </ABS>
<DATE1>   2 March 1994 </DATE1>
<F P=100> Nuclear Engineering </F>
<H3> <TI>   Production of Intermediate Heat Exchanger for HTTR Well Under Way </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94FE0279A Tokyo NIKKEI SANGYO SHIMBUN in Japanese 8 Dec 93 p 
5 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 94FE0279A </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIKKEI SANGYO SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:CSO 

  [Text] On 7 December JAERI disclosed the manufacturing 
status of the intermediate heat exchanger to be installed on the 
high temperature engineering test reactor (HTTR), which is a 
high temperature gas reactor research facility that JAERI is 
building at its O-arai Laboratory in Ibaraki Prefecture. At 
present the heat exchanger is about 55% completed and is 
scheduled to be transported to the construction site in 
September 1994. 
  The HTTR heat exchanger is being built at Yokohama Plant No. 
1 (Yokohama City) of Ishikawajima-Harima Heavy Industries. The 
device will transfer the heat from high temperature helium gas 
coming out of the reactor at 850-950C to a secondary helium 
gas system. The secondary helium gas will reach a temperature of 
900C and become a heat source for thermal systems other 
than those used for power generation. 
  These will be the highest temperatures in the world for a 
heat exchanger installed in a reactor to operate under. To 
assure durability under these high temperatures, the body of the 
heat exchanger has a two-layered structure, and the space 
between the inner and outer casings will be cooled by secondary 
helium gas flowing through pipes at about 400C. This design 
will help maintain the pressure-resistant outer casing at a 
lower temperature. 
  The high temperature gas reactor uses [omission] as fuel, 
graphite as the core structural material, and helium gas for 
cooling. It offers advantages because high temperature heat can 
be obtained for a variety of uses in addition to power 
generation. Construction began on the HTTR at the research 
facility in March 1991, and work is proceeding with a target of 
attaining initial criticality in 1998. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

