<DOCNO> FBIS3-21167 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "jpjst010__l94040" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   JPRS-JST-94-010L </AU>
Document Type:JPRS 
Document Title:Science &amp; Technology 

</HEADER>

<ABS>  Japan </ABS>
<DATE1>   8 March 1994 </DATE1>
<F P=100> Nuclear Engineering </F>
<H3> <TI>   MITI's Energy Agency To Cooperate with Asia for Nuclear Power Safety Technology </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94FE0171A Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 8 Nov 93 p 
3 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 94FE0171A </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:CSO 

  [Text] MITI's Agency of Natural Resources and Energy will 
provide cooperation on safety to Asian countries such as China 
and ROK that are proceeding with plans for nuclear power plants. 
The government has decided that if the construction of nuclear 
power plants in Asian countries does not proceed smoothly, it 
will hinder their domestic development of atomic energy as a 
source for power. Therefore, the government is considering 
technical cooperation through the private sector. Specific 
policy will be discussed on 11 November at the meeting of the 
Atomic Energy Subcommittee of the Advisory Committee for Energy 
(a MITI advisory body). 
  According to the Agency of Natural Resources and Energy, 
among the countries in Asia, China plans to construct a total of 
six nuclear power plants, including those presently under 
construction, in the future. In addition, by the year 2006 ROK 
will increase its capability to generate power from nuclear 
energy to 23,200,000 kW, roughly three times the current level, 
and both Indonesia and Malaysia plan to begin generating power 
by nuclear energy. 
  Not only is there concern that Japan's environment may be 
adversely affected by a nuclear accident in Asia, but such an 
accident will make construction of nuclear power plants in Japan 
that much more difficult. Therefore, the government is 
considering such methods as promoting exchange of human 
resources and technology transfer from the private sector in an 
effort to encourage international cooperation and ensure safe 
operation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

