Document Title:Science &amp; Technology 

</HEADER>

<ABS>  Japan </ABS>
<DATE1>   8 March 1994 </DATE1>
<F P=100> Superconductivity </F>
<H3> <TI>   NRIM Develops Wire Material Using Al/Pb/Bi Superconducting Alloy Produced in Space Shuttle </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94FE0179B Tokyo NIKKAN KOGYO SHIMBUN in Japanese 20 Nov 93 p 
2 </F>

<F P=103> 94FE0179B </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIKKAN KOGYO SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:CSO 

  [Text] On 19 November, the National Research Institute for 
Metals (NRIM) of the Science and Technology Agency announced the 
successful drawing of wire from an aluminum-lead-bismith-based 
superconducting ally that was produced in the space shuttle. 
Metals with differing specific gravities were the raw materials 
for producing, in the weightless environment of space, a 
superconducting alloy with uniform composition, and wire was 
drawn from this material after it had been recovered on earth. 
  Hopes had been placed on this alloy of aluminum, lead and 
bismuth for use in superconduction and vibration prevention. 
However, since the specific gravities of aluminum and lead are 
too disparate on the earth, attempts to produce a high-quality 
alloy have failed because the aluminum and lead separated into 
two layers. NRIM faced this challenge with the primary materials 
experiments conducted on the space shuttle Endeavor by astronaut 
Mori, and the alloy was produced in a weightless environment. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

