</HEADER>

<ABS>  Japan </ABS>
<DATE1>   8 March 1994 </DATE1>
<F P=100> Science &amp; Technology Policy/Economic Competitiveness </F>
<H3> <TI>   Riken's New Director General Outlines His Goals </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94FE0080G Tokyo NIKKEI SANGYO SHIMBUN in Japanese 2 Oct 93 p 
12 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 94FE0080G </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIKKEI SANGYO SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:CSO 

  [Text] On 1 October a press conference was held at the 
Science and Technology Agency by Akihito Arima and Minoru Oda, 
respectively the incoming and outgoing directors general of the 
Institute of Physical and Chemical Research (RIKEN) which 
represents Japan. Arima said he would continue Oda's policy of 
internationalization and outside evaluation. ``I'd like to 
create a Riken open wide to universities,'' said Arima. 
  Arima rated highly the internationalism of RIKEN which 
includes 200 foreign researchers. ``While pursuing 
internationalization, I'd also like to put energy into 
continuing the tradition of Drs. Shin'ichiro Asanaga and Hantaro 
Nagaoka through exchange with universities.'' 
  After Arima left the presidency of the University of Tokyo 
in 
March 1993, he returned to teaching as a professor at Hosei 
University. Even after becoming RIKEN's director general, during 
the school year he'll return to campus on Mondays to teach. 
  A report instigated by outgoing director Oda on the outside 
evaluation of RIKEN by Nobel prize winners and others was 
recently completed. It will be ``homework'' for Arima. ``I've 
been fortunate enough to have Professor Oda make a plan for 
improving the University of Tokyo's science faculty. I will take 
Professor Oda's `homework' very seriously,'' promised Arima. 

</TEXT>

